  "prompt": "What is the oldest book ever written?",
  "response": "Determining the \"oldest book ever written\" depends on how one defines a \"book\" and the criteria used, such as format, content, and cultural context. Here are some of the oldest known written works:\n\n1. **Epic of Gilgamesh** (circa 2100\u20131200 BCE):  \n   Written in ancient Mesopotamia, this epic poem is often considered one of the earliest surviving works of literature. It was inscribed on clay tablets in cuneiform script.\n\n2. **The Pyramid Texts** (circa 2400\u20132300 BCE):  \n   These are the oldest known religious texts, inscribed on the walls of Egyptian pyramids. They contain spells and rituals for the afterlife.\n\n3. **The Instructions of Shuruppak** (circa 2600\u20132500 BCE):  \n   This is one of the oldest surviving pieces of wisdom literature, written in Sumerian on clay tablets.\n\n4. **The Coffin Texts** (circa 2100 BCE):  \n   These ancient Egyptian funerary texts were inscribed on coffins and served as a guide for the deceased in the afterlife.\n\n5. **The Rigveda** (circa 1500\u20131200 BCE):  \n   One of the oldest sacred texts of Hinduism, composed in Vedic Sanskrit. It was initially transmitted orally before being written down.\n\n6. **The I Ching (Book of Changes)** (circa 1000\u2013800 BCE):  \n   An ancient Chinese divination text, it is one of the oldest Chinese books and a foundational work of Chinese philosophy.\n\n7. **The Ebla Tablets** (circa 2500 BCE):  \n   These clay tablets from the ancient city of Ebla (in modern-day Syria) contain administrative and literary texts, among the earliest known written records.\n\nIf we consider \"books\" in a more modern sense (bound or codices), the oldest surviving examples are from later periods, such as the **Codex Sinaiticus** (4th century CE), an early Christian manuscript of the Bible.\n\nThus, the oldest written works are typically ancient texts on clay tablets, papyrus, or other materials, with the Epic of Gilgamesh and the Pyramid Texts often cited as some of the earliest.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
